<br>
First off, the main argument against the free trade of the basics of need for humans isn't the innate right of adults to these goods/services wether they be medical, educational, clothing, or housing. It is to preserve the singular right of an individual to attain what level they are capable of through there own force of will and ability. In other words even in the most right wing society to suggest that medical care and education shouldn't be free to all is to suggest that not all are born equal, the singular fundemental argument in definition of the US (note I am not judging any of this just correcting some of the arguments made).<br>
<br>
As for the primary argument of socialism going against human nature, well... thats not exactly true, the nature of humans change according to there enviorment, placed in an enviorment where competition is the norm, and even encouraged it would only be considered natural for humans to compete at all levels and for all things. This is of course the crux of the argument going forward as the struggle of humanity as a race increasingly becomes man vs. man as opposed to man vs. enviorment. <br>
<br>
I should also point out that the statment &quot;competition brings out the best&quot; is farceical to the point of stupidity, the only place where I have even heard anyone able to give a plausable example of that is sports and I won't go into have assine that it would be to compare sports to life. The fact of the matter is that every example of a truely productive human race or sub set there of has been a co-opretive one, humanity is at its best when it works together not against itself which when viewed as such becomes rather obvious.<br>
<br>
Not judging anyones position just correcting some of the &quot;classic&quot; arguments often presented incorrectly.<br>
<br>
